# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bando-sport
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:bando-sport/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The **1904–1905 Welsh revival** was the largest Christian revival in Wales during the 20th century.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] It was one of the most dramatic in terms of its effect on the population, and triggered revivals in several other countries.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The movement kept the churches of Wales filled for many years to come, seats being placed in the aisles in Mount Pleasant Baptist Church in Swansea for twenty years or so, for example.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Meanwhile, the awakening swept the rest of Britain, Scandinavia, parts of Europe, North America, the mission fields of India and the Orient, Africa and Latin America.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The Welsh revival has been traced as the root of the megachurches in the present era.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The last revival in Wales was in 1859, but this followed other developments.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] From 1850 onwards, Christianity in Wales was markedly less Calvinistic in form.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] A generation of powerful biblical preachers ended, as leaders such as Christmas Evans (1766–1838), John Elias (1744–1841) and Henry Rees (1798–1869) died.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Between 1859 and 1904, there were local revivals in Cwmafan (1866), Rhondda (1879), Carmarthen and Blaenau Ffestiniog (1887), Dowlais (1890) and Pontnewydd (1892).
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] A prominent leader of the Revival was the Methodist preacher of New Quay, Joseph Jenkins, who arranged a conference in New Quay in 1903 with the theme to deepen loyalty to Christ.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] During a meeting in February 1904, Florrie Evans is quoted as having said, "I love Jesus Christ with all my heart", a statement which is recognized as having made an impression on the attendees.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] This event supposedly initiated the revival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The regular Sunday meetings, as well as the newly founded midweek meetings, became lively.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Members of Joseph Jenkins' church, led by Jenkins, traveled to other nearby towns and villages.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In September, a conference was held at Blaenannerch.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] It was reported that 'massive blessing' was upon this conference and the news quickly spread throughout the area and beyond.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The *South Wales Daily News* picked up on the events and reported that "the third great revival was afoot through the nation!".
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The other two noted revivals were the Welsh Methodist revival and the 1859 Methodist revival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In November 1904, Jenkins was invited to be a guest preacher at meetings in Bethany, Ammanford, the church of Nantlais Williams.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] When the appointment was arranged, there was no news yet of the conversions in New Quay and Blaenannerch, but an extra meeting was hastily arranged on the Sunday afternoon so that Joseph Jenkins could tell about the events.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Williams is recorded to have said that he was worried that there would be no interest in such a meeting and he was skeptical what the turnout would be.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] However, when he arrived, he could only just squeeze into the chapel to hear Jenkins.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] It had been arranged that Jenkins was to preach on the Monday night before his return to New Quay.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The church was again full with people professing their faith in Jesus.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Perhaps the most dramatic turn was when one of the crowd members announced, "Another meeting like this will be held here tomorrow night".
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] That meeting was also well attended and went on until the early hours of the next morning.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Despite already having been ordained as a minister, on that weekend in November 1904, Williams had a conversion experience, on the Saturday night prior to Jenkins' arrival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In December 1904, Joseph Jenkins embarked on three months of preaching and professing in areas of North Wales.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Many meetings were held in Amlwch, Llangefni, Llanerchymedd, Talysarn, Llanllyfni, Llanrwst, Denbigh, and Dinorwig, and some students at the University of Wales Bangor were converted.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] But perhaps the most conversions were seen in Bethesda; another leader of the revival, J.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Job, described the meeting held in Jerusalem, Bethesda on 22 December 1904 as "a hurricane".
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Evan Roberts was a young man influenced by the stories and experiences that were happening in New Quay and Blaenannerch.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] He decided to go to Newcastle Emlyn for ministerial training, and arrived in the revival in south Ceredigion.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The news of the mass conversions in New Quay and Blaenannerch had already spread to Newcastle Emlyn and were a distraction for a man who had been sent there to study.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Seth Joshua, another prominent leader of the revival, was invited to preach locally at a youth rally in Newquay, which Roberts had been given permission by the bible school to attend.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Seth had been praying for many years for God to give him Wales.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] After Evan's three months training at Newcastle Emlyn he was to return to Loughor to start his ministry.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] He claimed to have direct visions from the Holy Spirit: very specific visions, such as the number 100,000 representing the souls God intended to use him to save.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] As the revival unfolded, Roberts is said to have depended increasingly upon what he considered the guidance of the Holy Spirit.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Response to Roberts' ministry was initially slow, but soon the crowds turned out and the meetings were carried on until the early hours of the morning.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] After the meeting at Loughor, Roberts assembled a team and went on a tour of the South Wales valleys to spread the revival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Roberts did not take the decline of the revival well.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The great expectations of a worldwide revival that had arisen in his team were frustrated, and he afterwards fell into depression.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In 1913, when Roberts's mother was dying, his brother Dan tried to see him to ask him to visit his mother.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Eventually "Awstin", the reporter of the revival, gained access.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] There were rumours that Roberts was being held prisoner by the Penn-Lewises.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Roberts spoke freely about how God was preparing him for his next great work, and sent, via "Awstin", "God's message to the churches of south Wales".
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Because of Roberts's treatment of his mother, the message was ignored.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Aberdare became a major centre of the revival and the first area that Evan Roberts visited following his initial meetings at Loughor.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In the Aberdare area, the revival aroused alarm among ministers for the revolutionary, even anarchistic, impact it had upon chapel congregations and denominational organization.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In particular, it was seen as drawing attention away from pulpit preaching and the role of the minister.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The local newspaper, the *Aberdare Leader*, regarded the revival with suspicion from the outset, objecting to the 'abnormal heat' which it engendered.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Trecynon was particularly affected by the revival, and the meetings held there were said to have aroused more emotion and excitement than the more restrained meetings in Aberdare itself.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The impact of the revival was significant in the short term, but in the longer term was fairly transient.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] For the first time, the newspapers had a role in this revival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The *Western Mail* and the *South Wales Daily News*, Wales' daily newspapers, spread news of conversions and generated an air of excitement that helped to fuel the revival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The *Western Mail* in particular gave extensive coverage to Roberts' meetings in Loughor.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The articles were gathered together and published as a series of seven pamphlets, including copies of picture postcards of the revivalists that were published at the time.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The contents of the final pamphlet are credited by some as killing the revival.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Peter Price, a minister from Dowlais, wrote a letter that was very critical of Evan Roberts.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Price wanted to distinguish between the genuine revival that he believed was going on and a sham revival he associated with Evan Roberts.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The pamphlet contains many letters in support of Evan Roberts (the majority), and a few supporting Price.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Vyrynwy Morgan gives further letters supporting Price.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The Welsh revival has been described not as an isolated religious movement, but as very much a part of Britain's modernisation.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The revival began in late 1904 under the leadership of Evan Roberts (1878–1951), a 26-year-old former collier and minister in training.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The revival lasted less than a year, but in that time 100,000 people were converted.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Begun as an effort to kindle non-denominational, non-sectarian spirituality, the Welsh revival of 1904–05 coincided with the rise of the labour movement, socialism, and a general disaffection with religion among the working class and youths.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Placed in context, the short-lived revival appears as both a climax for nonconformism and a flashpoint of change in Welsh religious life.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The movement spread to Scotland and England, with estimates that a million people were converted in Britain.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Missionaries subsequently carried the movement abroad; it was especially influential on the Pentecostal movement emerging in California.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Unlike earlier religious revivals based on powerful preaching, the revival of 1904–05 relied primarily on music and on alleged supernatural phenomena as exemplified by the visions of Evan Roberts.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The intellectual emphasis of the earlier revivals had left a dearth of religious imagery that the visions supplied.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The visions also challenged the denial of the spiritual and miraculous element of Scripture by opponents of the revival, who held liberal and critical theological positions.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The structure and content of the visions not only repeated those of Scripture and earlier Christian mystical tradition but also illuminated the personal and social tensions that the revival addressed by juxtaposing Biblical images with scenes familiar to contemporary Welsh believers.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The after-effects of the revival were considered by Vyrynwy Morgan in the final chapter of his book, which gives the figures for convictions for drunkenness in the county of Glamorgan for the years 1902 to 1907, supplied by the police.
[src:bando-sport/1904-1905-welsh-revival] There is a near 50% reduction after the revival.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:bando-sport/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] A traditional "bucket and spade" resort for the South Wales Valleys during the 1940s, '50s and '60s, Aberavon Beach was once an area of sand dunes known as Aberavon Burrows.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Changing economic and social conditions led to the decline of the resort, but in 1998 the local authority published a strategy to improve the physical environment of the area and increase tourism.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] New facilities completed since then have included an amphitheatre, piazza and skateboard park, while a six-screen Reel Cinema opened next to the Afan Lido as part of a development called "Hollywood Park".
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] However, associated plans for a bowling alley have failed to progress and restaurant franchises on the site have struggled, leading one businessman to claim that the seafront regeneration scheme has been a "white elephant".
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] The beachfront also houses a hotel and a small number of cafes, bars and restaurants.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Concerns have been expressed about coastal erosion affecting Aberavon Beach and various other beaches in Swansea Bay.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] In December 2009, more than 100 firefighters tackled a fire at the Afan Lido after a blaze broke out at the pool.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] The fire at the lido broke through the roof and fire crews were unable to enter the building.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Seventeen fire vehicles including three aerial appliances were at the scene and firefighters remained at the scene for some 32-hours after the fire broke out.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] At the time of the fire the lido was open but had just one person swimming.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] A lifeguard on duty spotted flames coming up from behind a fake rock feature and raised the alarm.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] As fire crews arrived at the scene residents were told to remain indoors and to keep doors and windows closed due to potentially dangerous chemicals.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Approximately an hour after the fire started residents in the nearby Channel View area had to be evacuated from their homes due to the chemicals inside the building.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] A restaurant which was located a few hundred metres from the Afan Lido complex also had to be evacuated.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] As the fire was happening local council members promised that the Afan Lido would be replaced.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Soon after the fire, the building was condemned and marked as structurally unsafe.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Soon plans were being drawn up for a new Afan Lido with hopes for it to be completed by the summer 2013.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] In October 2011, after almost two years demolition finally began, clearing the site had previously been hampered by the presence of asbestos.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Work to remove it was completed and the building was fully demolished by January 2012.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] After extensive public consultations through 2012 a replacement facility is due to begin construction in April 2014 – making use of the defunct bowling alley site.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] The site of the original complex will be sold to help offset the cost of the new build.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] The Kitetail sculpture at Aberavon seafront is Wales' largest sculpture standing at 12 metres (40 ft) high and weighing 11 tonnes (1,700 st).
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-beach] Designed by Carmarthenshire-based artist and sculptor Andrew Rowe, it was installed in December 2007.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The club was founded in 1876 as Afan Football Club, and changed names several times before settling on Aberavon Rugby Football Club.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] They joined the Welsh Rugby Union in 1887.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Although not a founding member of the Welsh Rugby Union, rugby has been played at Aberavon since before the union's conception.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In the 1870s Mansel tinplate works was built in the area, and its proprietors, Col.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] David and Sir Sidney Byass encouraged the local workers to form a rugby team.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The earliest game being recorded in the Western Mail when on the 17/11/1877, Aberavon played away and lost to Maesteg.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Like many early Welsh clubs the teams met at a local hotel, originally the dour Castle Hotel before moving to the more luxurious Hong Kong Hotel.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1882 Aberavon took part in the South Wales Challenge Cup, their first competitive game, and in the 1886/87 season Aberavon RFC applied to and were accepted into the WRU.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] By 1897 Aberavon RFC were able to boast their first capped player, when Dan Jones was selected for Wales to play against England.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1907 Aberavon RFC moved to the Central Athletic Ground and in 1913 Miss Emily Charlotte Talbot gave exclusive rights to the club to use the pitch and granted them a lease for 39 years, giving needed stability.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] An indicator of Aberavon's growing success occurred in 1908, when a joint Neath/Aberavon team was chosen as one of the teams to face the first touring Australian side.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The match turned out to be an ill played affair with poor discipline on all sides, the Wallabies eventually won the game 15–0.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1914 following the outbreak of World War I, the committee of Aberavon RFC decided that rugby football should cease until the end of hostilities.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] During the war years their ground was sectioned off to be made into allotments to help the war effort.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1921 the Central Athletic Ground was relaid and a stand erected; Aberavon RFC returned to their home ground.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Taylor of The Evening Post, dubbed the club *The Wizards of the West*.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The name stuck and was shortened sometimes to 'The Welsh Wizards' or just 'The Wizards', the nickname stays with the club to this day.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1932 Aberavon Supporters Club reformed, after an initial attempt failed in 1920, and by 1932 they had begun producing the first official match programme.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] 1935 saw The Central Athletic ground being renamed the Talbot Athletic Ground.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1952 Aberavon RFC changed their shirt colours for the final time to red and black hoops; and later that year succeeded in becoming the absolute owners of the Talbot Athletic ground.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The expansion of the local steel works in the 1950s also aided in bringing new enthusiasts to the area and this was reflected in one of Aberavon RFC's most successful periods.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Twice in the 1970s Aberavon reached the final of the WRU Challenge Cup.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] On both occasions, in 1974 and 1975, the club lost by a slight margin to the tournament's most successful team Llanelli.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1976 Aberavon played the Argentina national team which toured Wales and England and lost by 18 points to 6.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] However, in the same season they defeated the touring Italian national team.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 1988 disagreement between leading players and the club's committee over sponsorship issues and more generally the style and structure of the club's management escalated into a bitter dispute that ended with the majority of the previous season's squad leaving the club.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] As a result, Aberavon struggled for much of the following season, although they did upset the odds by defeating a touring Western Samoan team by 22 points to 11 on 26 October 1988.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] This in turn led to the club being incorporated as a limited company run by a board of directors, which was essentially what the players were seeking in 1988.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In May 2002 Aberavon and Pontypool finished at the top of Division 1 on the same number of league points and the same number of tries but the Wizards took the title on a better for/against points ratio.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Aberavon then faced a two-legged play-off with Caerphilly, who had been relegated from the Premier Division.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Aberavon lost the play-off (66-27 on aggregate) and remained in Division 1 for the 2002/3 season.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The play-off was scrapped after this season.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In May 2003, the same scenario as the previous season occurred with both Pontypool and Aberavon locked in a two horse race for the title.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Due to the clubs' original January fixture being rearranged, the league title would be decided in a winner-takes-all clash at the Talbot Athletic Ground on 13 May 2003.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] They finished the 2002/3 season as Division 1 runners up after winning the championship the previous two seasons.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Small red toy wizards adorn the tops of the rugby posts at their ground, and the figure of a wizard has adorned the players' kit as the club's emblem since the mid-1970s.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] One theory of the nickname 'The Wizards' is thought to have been based on the many workers who came to Port Talbot in the 19th century from the Carmarthen area, strongly associated with the legendary wizard Merlin.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] So many of them lived in one street that it was named 'Carmarthen Row'; Talbot Athletic Ground was built near Carmarthen Row.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The more generally accepted view, however, is that the nickname was coined by South Wales Evening Post reporter Bill Taylor during the 1920s, when he dubbed the highly successful Aberavon team of that era "The Wizards of the West".
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] The below list contains players that have represented Aberavon and have been capped at international level.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Since the restructuring of the game in Wales, the route for club players to gain international honours is via the game's professional tier, therefore it is unlikely that any future player will be selected for international rugby directly from the club.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] However, in recent years representative honours have come in the form of invitations to play for the world-famous Barbarians FC.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] In 2006 Richard Morris was called up to represent the Barbarians in the annual Remembrance Match, scoring the first and last tries in a 33–25 victory.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] Two years later it was the turn of lock Chris Gittins to represent the Wizards in the same fixture in a 33–14 victory.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon-rfc] 1 These matches were played by a joint Neath/Aberavon team.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Little is known about Aberavon before Norman times.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Bronze Age remains have been found in the hills behind the town.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Roman artifacts have been found near the sea, including when the docks were being built in the 19th century.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] About 1090 the invading Normans deposed Iestyn ap Gwrgant, the ruler of Glamorgan.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] His son, Caradog ab Iestyn, was the only Welsh lord to retain lands in Glamorgan – the area between the Afan and Neath rivers – and he became the first of the Lords of Afan.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Caradoc built a castle in Aberafan near the present site of St Mary's Church.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] This wooden castle was burnt down in 1153 and Caradoc's son, Morgan ap Caradoc, rebuilt the castle in stone.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] In 1147, Cistercian monks founded the nearby Margam Abbey.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] In 1241, the Lordship passed to Morgan Fychan.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] His son, Leisan D'Avene, was the first known by a Norman-style surname.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] In 1304, Leisian D'Avene adopted the town's first charter.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] By 1373, the town had passed into the hands of Edward le Despencer, Lord of Glamorgan, and the Lords of Afan had ceased to be.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The English antiquarian John Leland made an extensive journey through Wales c.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] 1536–1539, of which he recorded an itinerary.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] He passed through Aberafan, which he describes as a "poor village" surrounded by barren ground, though he also describes the area as heavily wooded, not much of which remains today.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] He mentions the use of the river mouth as a port, a "haven for ships" as he puts it.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] His portrayal of Aberafan as a small, struggling village however suggests that the port was not in great use, especially as traffic to and from Margam Abbey would have ceased following its dissolution in 1536.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Tradition has it that when the English Civil War broke out in 1648 Oliver Cromwell tried to seize the town charter as he passed through the town on his way to Pembroke, but it was hidden from him in a chopping block.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberafan also endured the storm surge of 1607 and the Great Flood of 1768, when the river flowed into St Mary's Church.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon was the birthplace of Dic Penderyn, a key figure in the Merthyr Rising of 1831.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] St Mary's Church is the site of his grave.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The castle site was built over between 1876 and 1897 and its foundations now lie underneath the streets around the church.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] There have been reports of a ghost, a white lady seen floating above the castle ruins.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The ghost is speculated to be Jane de Afan, the last occupant of Aberavon Castle.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] In the 18th century industry began to appear in the area.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Industrialists worked with the Talbot family of Margam Castle to divert the bottom of the Afan river to its present bed, and in 1836 opened a new harbour east of the river Afan with the name of "Port Talbot".
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The following decades saw significant industrial and population growth for Aberafan and the surrounding areas with people coming from North and West Wales, South West England, and Ireland.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] A new borough of Aberavon came into being in 1861, though at the time it was still smaller than nearby Cwmafan or Taibach.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Although there were small local collieries the area had become known for its metalworking industry.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] In the 1950s many of the sand dunes of Aberavon Beach disappeared as part of the development of the Sandfields estate, at this time a 1+1⁄4-mile (2-kilometre) sea wall was built primarily for sea defences.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The estate was built to accommodate the growing population, especially the families of workers at the new Port Talbot Steelworks.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] From 1832 Aberavon had belonged to the Swansea parliamentary district of boroughs, uniting with Kenfig, Loughor, Neath and Swansea to return one member; from 1918 to 2024 it had its own UK parliament constituency.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Starting in 2024 it was part of the Aberafan Maesteg constituency.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Its most famous MP was Ramsay MacDonald.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Sir Geoffrey Howe, who although born locally never represented the town in the House of Commons, chose as his peerage title Lord Howe of Aberavon.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Since 1999 it has had its own Welsh Assembly constituency.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon hosted the National Eisteddfod in 1932 and 1966.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon RFC are a rugby union team, and play in the Welsh Premier Division.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon Quins RFC are a rugby union club based at Harlequin Road and play their rugby in the WRU Division Two West league.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon Green Stars RFC are a rugby club based in Sitwell Way Aberavon.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Afan Lido F.C. is a football team, playing in Cymru South.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] One of Aberavon's rugby league clubs is called the Aberavon Fighting Irish and play in the Welsh Conference Premier.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon & Port Talbot Golf Club (now defunct) was founded in 1905.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The course closed following WW2 and the land was used for housing.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The Baglan Bay Industrial Park lies on a stretch of Baglan Moors in the parish of Aberavon south east of the Baglan Energy Park and immediately northwest of Neath Port Talbot Hospital.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] It is sandwiched between the M4 Motorway and Afan Way (A4241).
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The electoral ward of Aberavon is coterminous with district of Aberavon and is a part of the Welsh parliamentary constituency of Aberavon.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] Aberavon is bounded by the wards of Sandfields West and Sandfields East to the southwest; Baglan to the north; Port Talbot to the east and Margam to the south.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The ward boundaries can be defined by the roads surrounding it which are the M4 Motorway to the north east; the A4241 to the north west; Afan Way to the southwest and the River Afan to the south east.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The Aberavon ward can be roughly divided into two parts.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] There is the residential area to the southeastern part of the ward beside the River Afan.
[src:bando-sport/aberavon] The north western area consists of areas of industrial estate land called the Baglan Industrial Park which includes a number of out of town retail premises as well as business and manufacturing premises.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:bando-sport/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:bando-sport/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] A bando game is played on a large level field between teams of up to thirty players each of them equipped with a *bando*: a curve-ended stick resembling that used in field hockey.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Although no formal rules are known, the objective of the game was to strike a ball between two marks which served as goals at either end of the pitch.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Popular in Glamorgan in the nineteenth century, the sport all but vanished by the end of the century.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Bando is believed to have common origins with the English game of bandy.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Whereas the sticks were made of hard wood, the ball, known as a "colby", was normally of yew, box or crabapple.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The sport was often played between local villages, with fierce rivalries in the west of Glamorgan between Baglan, Aberavon and Margam and in mid Glamorgan between Pyle, Kenfig and Llangynwyd.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Edward Matthews of Ewenni records that no-one above the age of twelve-month would be seen without a bando stick.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Although many pre-industrial games are recorded to be lawless affairs with haphazard rules, the contrary appears true with bando.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Once a challenge of a game was made between villages, wagers were normally set which demanded an agreed set of rules, including the number of players, normally between 20 and 30 and the size of the playing area.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Matthews records a playing area of 200 yards, with the goal markers at each end set ten yards apart.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Despite a set of rules, the game was still open to violent play with players often using their bando sticks to strike their opponents.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] One of the more notable teams of the time were the **"Margam Bando Boys"**, a team who played on Aberavon Beach.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The team are celebrated in a macaronic ballad, "The Margam Bando Boys", written in the earlier part of the nineteenth century.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Bando is believed to be the first mass spectator sport of Glamorgan and Wales, and in 1817 a match between Margam and Newton Nottage attracted over 3,000 spectators.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The sport remained popular throughout the century with notable personalities known to play the sport including preacher John Elias and future prime minister, David Lloyd George.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The sport continued to be played until the second half of the nineteenth century, but was beginning to be replaced by other sports.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The game survived in the Aberavon area until the death of Theodore Talbot, the captain of the Margam Bando Boys in 1876.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Talbot, the son of Christopher Rice Mansel Talbot and heir to the Margam Estate was a supporter of the sport, and his death coincided with the coming of the Mansel, Avon Vale and Taibach tinworks.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The employees turned to a new sport spreading through south Wales, rugby union, with Aberavon Rugby Football Club forming in 1876.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Despite having no religious links with Easter, the sport became a tradition on the date as part of some parish festivals, unlike traditional West-Walian games such as Smeit, which were generally banned on Sundays.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] In 2025, Campau Celtaidd Cymru (CCC) was founded with the aim of reviving the ancient sports of Wales, including Bando.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The cultural and sporting organisation hosted a Bando tournament at Margam Cricket Club on 28 May 2025 to coincide with Eisteddfod yr Urdd Dur a Môr, which was held between 26 and 31 May 2025 at Margam Park.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] Pupils from three local primary schools competed in the tournament, which marked the official launch of CCC.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] The tournament represented the first organised games of Bando in over a century.
[src:bando-sport/bando-sport] CCC hope to recreate some *bandis* (the playing sticks) based on an original in the near future with a view to a historical re-enactment of the ancient version of the game, probably on Cynffig beach.
